  <!-- Tech stack -->
  <section class="bg-cream mashrabiya py-8 sm:py-10">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 id="stack" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">How Misbaha is built</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-forest/80">
        A modern React Native stack, shipped to iOS and Android from a single codebase.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
        {
          techStack.map((s) => (
            <div class="rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/50 p-5">
              <h3 class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide text-forest/55 uppercase">
                {s.group}
              </h3>
              <ul class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
                {s.items.map((item) => (
                  <li class="rounded-full border border-forest/15 bg-cream/60 px-3 py-1 text-sm text-forest">
                    {item}
                  </li>
                ))}
              </ul>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-cream mashrabiya py-8 sm:py-10">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
      <!-- Plain intro -->
      <div class="space-y-4 text-forest/90">
        <h2 id="about" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">What this is about</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Before we ship an update to Misbaha (a digital prayer-bead and supplications app),
          a fleet of automated tests "uses" the app the way a person would: opening it,
          tapping around, counting, creating goals, searching. If a test fails, it should
          mean the app is broken. The trouble is that tests can also fail for reasons that
          have nothing to do with the app — and telling those apart is most of the work.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          To measure how trustworthy our app really is, we run each of 5 core journeys 30
          times — 150 runs in total. A reliable app should pass all of them, every time.
          Ours kept hovering between 84% and 95%. Below is everything that stood between us
          and a clean 100%, grouped into a simple category so you can see the pattern:
          <strong>most failures were never the app at all.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Result headline -->
      <div class="mt-8 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/60 p-6 text-center">
          <p class="text-xs tracking-wide text-forest/60 uppercase">Where we started</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-serif text-4xl font-semibold text-[#c0392b]">84%</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-forest/70">126 of 150 runs</p>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center justify-center">
          <span class="font-serif text-3xl text-gold">&rarr;</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/60 p-6 text-center">
          <p class="text-xs tracking-wide text-forest/60 uppercase">Where we landed</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-serif text-4xl font-semibold text-[#1e8449]">100%</p>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-forest/70">150 of 150 runs</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Methodology -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="method" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">How we test</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          Reliability is not a single number you check once — it is something you have to
          measure carefully and repeatedly. Here is the approach in plain terms.
        </p>
        <dl class="mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          {
            methodology.map((m) => (
              <div class="rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/50 p-5">
                <dt class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold text-forest">{m.title}</dt>
                <dd class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-forest/80">{m.body}</dd>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </dl>
      </div>

      <!-- The five journeys -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="journeys" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">The five journeys</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          These are the five things we make sure work, every single time, before any update
          reaches our users.
        </p>
        <ol class="mt-6 space-y-3">
          {
            journeys.map((j) => (
              <li class="flex items-start gap-4 rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/50 p-5">
                <span class="flex h-9 w-9 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-forest font-serif text-sm font-semibold text-cream">
                  {j.n}
                </span>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold text-forest">{j.title}</h3>
                  <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-forest/80">{j.desc}</p>
                </div>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- Results by journey -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="results" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">Results by journey</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          Each journey ran 30 times before our fixes (baseline) and 30 times after
          (hardened). The pattern is clear: every journey reached a perfect score.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-forest/10">
          <table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-forest text-cream">
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-left font-semibold">Journey</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-left font-semibold">What it checks</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold">Baseline</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold">Hardened</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {
                results.map((r, i) => (
                  <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-white/60' : 'bg-cream/40'}>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium text-forest">{r.journey}</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-forest/70">{r.checks}</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right whitespace-nowrap text-[#c0392b]">
                      {r.basePass}/{RUNS_PER} ({pct(r.basePass, RUNS_PER)}%)
                    </td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold whitespace-nowrap text-[#1e8449]">
                      {r.hardPass}/{RUNS_PER} (100%)
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                ))
              }
              <tr class="border-t-2 border-forest/20 bg-white/80">
                <td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-serif font-semibold text-forest" colspan="2">All journeys</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold whitespace-nowrap text-[#c0392b]">
                  {baseTotal}/{RUNS_PER * results.length} ({pct(baseTotal, RUNS_PER * results.length)}%)
                </td>
                <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold whitespace-nowrap text-[#1e8449]">
                  {hardTotal}/{RUNS_PER * results.length} (100%)
                </td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-forest/55">
          Baseline = the run before the final round of fixes (84.6% overall). Hardened = the
          run after all 13 issues were resolved (100% overall, with no connection errors).
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Reliability metrics -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="scorecard" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">The reliability scorecard</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          Pass rate is only part of the story. These are the measures QA engineers use to
          judge whether a test suite can be trusted — before our fixes, and after.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-forest/10">
          <table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-forest text-cream">
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-left font-semibold">Measure</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-left font-semibold">What it means</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold">Baseline</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold">Hardened</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {
                metrics.map((m, i) => (
                  <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-white/60' : 'bg-cream/40'}>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 font-medium text-forest">{m.name}</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-forest/70">{m.meaning}</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right whitespace-nowrap text-[#c0392b]">{m.base}</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-2.5 text-right font-semibold whitespace-nowrap text-[#1e8449]">
                      {m.hard}
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                ))
              }
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-forest/55">
          The most telling row is "false alarms": every one of the baseline's 23 failures
          was the test giving up too early, not a real problem in the app.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Per-issue before/after -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="issues" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">Every issue, before and after</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          Each card shows the problem in plain terms, then a picture of what was happening
          <span class="font-semibold text-[#c0392b]">before</span> the fix and what happens
          <span class="font-semibold text-[#1e8449]">after</span> — followed by the technical
          detail for engineers.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-6 space-y-3">
          {
            issues.map((issue, i) => (
              <details id={issue.id} class="issue-card scroll-mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/60">
                <summary class="flex cursor-pointer list-none flex-wrap items-center gap-3 p-5 sm:p-6">
                  <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gold/15 font-serif text-sm font-semibold text-gold">
                    {i + 1}
                  </span>
                  <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-semibold text-forest sm:text-2xl">{issue.title}</h3>
                  <span class="rounded-full border border-forest/15 bg-cream px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-forest/70">
                    {issue.category}
                  </span>
                  <span class="ml-auto flex items-center gap-2 text-gold">
                    <span class="expand-label text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide uppercase">
                      Expand for details
                    </span>
                    <span class="hint-bounce flex h-7 w-7 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gold/15">
                      <svg class="chevron h-4 w-4" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true">
                        <path d="M5 8l5 5 5-5" />
                      </svg>
                    </span>
                  </span>
                </summary>

                <div class="px-5 pb-5 sm:px-6 sm:pb-6">
                  <p class="leading-relaxed text-forest/85">{issue.plain}</p>

                  <div class="mt-6 grid gap-5 lg:grid-cols-2">
                    <div class="rounded-2xl border-l-4 border-[#c0392b] bg-[#fdecea]/40 p-4">
                      <p class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide text-[#c0392b] uppercase">Before</p>
                      <div class="mt-3" set:html={issue.beforeSvg} />
                    </div>
                    <div class="rounded-2xl border-l-4 border-[#1e8449] bg-[#e9f7ef]/40 p-4">
                      <p class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide text-[#1e8449] uppercase">After</p>
                      <div class="mt-3" set:html={issue.afterSvg} />
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <p class="mt-5 text-sm text-forest/85">
                    <span class="font-semibold text-forest">The fix:</span> {issue.fix}
                  </p>

                  <details class="group mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-cream/60 p-4">
                    <summary class="cursor-pointer list-none font-semibold text-forest">
                      <span class="text-gold">›</span> Tech details
                    </summary>
                    <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-forest/80">{issue.tech}</p>
                  </details>
                </div>
              </details>
            ))
          }
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Failure taxonomy -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="taxonomy" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">Sorting failures by type</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          Good QA work does not just count failures — it sorts them into standard types, so
          you know whether to fix the app, the test, or the machine. Here is where our 13
          issues landed, including two types we designed out entirely.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-3">
          {
            taxonomy.map((tx) => (
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4 rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/50 p-5">
                <span
                  class={`flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full font-serif text-lg font-semibold ${tx.count === 0 ? 'bg-cream text-forest/50 ring-1 ring-forest/15' : 'bg-forest text-cream'}`}
                >
                  {tx.count}
                </span>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold text-forest">{tx.cls}</h3>
                  <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-forest/80">{tx.note}</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </div>
        <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-forest/55">
          Classification coverage: 100% — every failure was explained, none left as
          "unknown".
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Category legend -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="categories" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">How to read the categories</h2>
        <dl class="mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          {
            categories.map((c) => (
              <div class="rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/50 p-5">
                <dt class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold text-forest">{c.name}</dt>
                <dd class="mt-1 text-sm text-forest/80">{c.desc}</dd>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </dl>
      </div>

      <!-- Environment & harness -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="setup" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">The exact setup</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          For anyone who wants to reproduce this, here is precisely what was tested and how.
        </p>
        <dl class="mt-6 grid gap-px overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-forest/10 sm:grid-cols-2">
          {
            environment.map((e) => (
              <div class="bg-white/70 p-4">
                <dt class="text-xs font-semibold tracking-wide text-forest/55 uppercase">{e.k}</dt>
                <dd class="mt-1 text-sm font-medium text-forest">{e.v}</dd>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </dl>
      </div>

      <!-- Limitations & next steps -->
      <div class="mt-8">
        <h2 id="limitations" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold text-forest">Honest limitations</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-forest/80">
          A trustworthy report says what it cannot yet claim. These are the open trade-offs.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-6 space-y-3">
          {
            limitations.map((l) => (
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3 rounded-2xl border border-forest/10 bg-white/50 p-4">
                <span class="mt-1 h-2 w-2 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-gold" />
                <span class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-forest/80">{l}</span>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Takeaway -->
      <div class="mt-8 rounded-3xl bg-forest p-6 text-cream sm:p-8">
        <h2 id="takeaway" class="scroll-mt-24 font-serif text-3xl font-semibold">The takeaway</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-cream/85">
          Of the 13 problems we fixed, only a couple were genuine app bugs. The rest were
          the testing setup itself: machines overloaded, tools misconfigured, and an
          automation engine quietly tripping over its own feet. That is the real lesson of
          reliability work — before you can trust what a test says about your app, you have
          to make the test itself trustworthy.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-cream/85">
          Once we did, the picture was unambiguous: <strong class="text-gold-light">150 out
          of 150 runs passed, with no connection errors at all.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    .issue-card > summary {
      list-style: none;
    }
    .issue-card > summary::-webkit-details-marker {
      display: none;
    }
    .issue-card > summary {
      transition: background-color 0.2s ease;
    }
    .issue-card > summary:hover {
      background-color: rgb(247 243 233 / 0.5);
    }
    .issue-card .chevron {
      transition: transform 0.25s ease;
    }
    .issue-card[open] .chevron {
      transform: rotate(180deg);
    }
    .issue-card[open] .hint-bounce {
      animation: none;
      background-color: transparent;
    }
    .issue-card[open] .expand-label {
      display: none;
    }
    .hint-bounce {
      animation: hint-bounce 1.6s ease-in-out infinite;
    }
    @keyframes hint-bounce {
      0%,
      100% {
        transform: translateY(0);
      }
      50% {
        transform: translateY(3px);
      }
    }
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .hint-bounce {
        animation: none;
      }
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
